Note that the honeycomb lattice $hl$ is bipartite. The summand in @pfnhoney can be written as,
$
 product_l W(sigma_l|sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k) 
$<wformpfn>
where the product is over the red vertices $l$ in @startridiag and the Boltzmann weight $W$ is defined as,
$
  W(sigma_l|sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k) = exp[sigma_l (L_1 sigma_i + L_2 sigma_j + L_3 sigma_k)]
$
Let us denote the set of  black vertices by $A$ and the set of red vertices by $B$. Note during the summation written in  the form of @wformpfn, the spin $sigma_l$ appears in only one factor of the product.  We can then sum over the spins in the set $B$ to obtain the partition function as,
$
  Z_N^hl ({L}) = sum_(sigma in A) w(sigma_i,sigma_j,sigma_k)
$<pfnw>
where the Boltzmann weight $w$ is defined as,
$
  w(sigma_i,sigma_j,sigma_k) &= sum_(sigma_l in B) W(sigma_l|sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k)\
  &= 2 cosh(L_1 sigma_i + L_2 sigma_j + L_3 sigma_k)
$<boltzwform>
The sum in @pfnw is over the spins in the set $A$ which are the black vertices in @startridiag. $sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k$ are the spins in the three edges connected to the red vertex $l$ in each star in $hl$. Note from @boltzwform that $w(-sigma_i, -sigma_j, -sigma_k) = w(sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k)$. This means that there we can write $w(sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k)$ as,
$
  w(sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k) = R exp(K_1 sigma_j sigma_k + K_2 sigma_i sigma_k + K_3 sigma_i sigma_j)
$<startriweight>
where $R,K_1,K_2,K_3$ are found later, which causes this identity to hold true for all spins $sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k$. The partition function for $hl$ is then given by,
$
  Z_N^hl ({L}) = R^(N\/2) sum_(sigma in A) product_{i,j,k} exp(K_1 sigma_i sigma_j + K_2 sigma_i sigma_k + K_3 sigma_j sigma_k)
$
This is exactly the partition function for the triangular lattice $tl$ with $N\/2$ sites @pfntri. Then we can relate the partition function of $hl$ on $2N$ spins with the partition function of $tl$ on $N$ spins as,
$
  Z_(2N)^hl ({L}) = R^N Z_N^tl ({K})
$<strel>

This is known as the star triangle relation. The relation holds true for all spins $sigma_i, sigma_j, sigma_k$ and thus the Boltzmann weights $R,K_1,K_2,K_3$ are independent of the spins. 

